how do you get relative line numbers in neovim?

Gemini said
Getting relative line numbers is one of the most common "quality of life" improvements in Neovim, especially for Arch users who want to navigate code with surgical precision.

Relative line numbers allow you to see how many lines away a target is from your cursor, making vertical jumps (like typing 12j or 5k) much more intuitive.

1. The "Quick Fix" (Command Line)
If you want to try it out immediately without editing your config, type this while inside Neovim:

Vim Script
:set relativenumber
2. The Permanent Way (Lua Config)
For a persistent setup on Arch, you’ll want to add these lines to your init.lua (usually located at ~/.config/nvim/init.lua).

Most users prefer "Hybrid Mode," which shows the absolute line number for your current line and relative numbers for everything else.

Lua
-- Enable relative line numbers
vim.opt.number = true          -- Shows the absolute line number of the current line
vim.opt.relativenumber = true   -- Shows relative numbers for all other lines
Why use Hybrid Mode?
Navigation: You immediately know that the function 15 lines down requires exactly 15j to reach.

Context: By keeping vim.opt.number = true, you still know exactly which line of the file you are currently on (e.g., line 402), which is helpful for debugging or error logs.

Bonus: Toggle with a Keymap
Sometimes relative numbers can be distracting (like when pair programming). You can add a toggle to your init.lua:

Lua
vim.keymap.set("n", "<leader>rn", ":set relativenumber!<CR>", { desc = "Toggle relative line numbers" })
