Since you've got those relative line numbers staring back at you, it’s time to stop hitting j and k repeatedly like a frantic gamer. In Neovim, we want to move with intent.

Here are the "classic" motions and some custom tweaks to make you feel like a wizard on your Arch setup.

1. The Bread and Butter: Vertical Jumps
Now that you see the numbers, you use the format [Number][Direction].

15j: Jump down 15 lines.

8k: Jump up 8 lines.

d5j: Delete the current line and the 5 lines below it.

y3k: Yank (copy) the current line and the 3 lines above it.

2. Smarter Vertical Navigation
Standard j and k can be annoying when you have wrapped lines (one long line of code taking up two visual lines). By default, Neovim skips the "visual" line. Add these to your init.lua to move by visual lines instead:

Lua
-- Move by visual lines, not logical lines (great for wrapped text)
vim.keymap.set("n", "k", "v:count == 0 ? 'gk' : 'k'", { expr = true, silent = true })
vim.keymap.set("n", "j", "v:count == 0 ? 'gj' : 'j'", { expr = true, silent = true })
3. The "Power User" Movements
Beyond just jumping to a number, these help you fly through files:

Key	Action
H	Move cursor to the High (top) of the screen.
M	Move cursor to the Middle of the screen.
L	Move cursor to the Low (bottom) of the screen.
{ / }	Jump to the previous/next empty paragraph (great for skipping functions).
%	Jump between matching brackets () [] {}.
4. Centering the Screen (The Pro Move)
When jumping long distances (like 30j), your eyes often lose the cursor because it hits the bottom of the screen. You can force the cursor to stay centered:

Lua
-- Keep the cursor centered when jumping half-pages
vim.keymap.set("n", "<C-d>", "<C-d>zz")
vim.keymap.set("n", "<C-u>", "<C-u>zz")

-- Keep search terms centered
vim.keymap.set("n", "n", "nzzzv")
vim.keymap.set("n", "N", "Nzzzv")
5. Horizontal Precision
Don't use the arrow keys to get to the end of a line. Use these:

0: Start of the line (absolute).

^: Start of the line (first non-blank character).

$: End of the line.

f + [char]: Find the next instance of that character (e.g., f( jumps to the next parenthesis).

